07055nam a22010455i 9789048542024DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20202020ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485420247 a10.1515/97890485420242doi  a(DE-B1597)571586  a(OCoLC)1200747199  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 4aPN1995.25bT544 2020 7aART0570002bisacsh04a791.4365722300aTheorizing Film Through Contemporary Art :bExpanding Cinema /ced. by Jill Murphy, Laura Rascaroli. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (302 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aFilm Culture in Transition00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tForeword: Courtesy of the Artists -- tIntroduction: On Cinema Expanding -- tPart One Materialities -- t1 Cinema as (In)Visible Object -- t2 Objects in Time -- t3 Materializing the Body of the Actor -- t4 How to Spell 'Film' -- tPart Two Immaterialities -- t5 The Magic of Shadows -- t6 Douglas Gordon and the Gallery of the Mind -- t7 A Throw of the Dice Will Never Abolish Chance -- tPart Three Temporalities -- t8 The Photo-Filmic Diorama -- t9 The Cinematic Dispositif and Its Ghost -- t10 Time/Frame: On Cinematic Duration -- tPart Four The Futures of the Image -- t11 Interactivity without Control -- t12 Post-Cinematic Unframing -- t13 Absolute Immanence -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs the cinematic experience becomes subsumed into ubiquitous technologies of seeing, contemporary artworks lift the cinematic from the immateriality of the film screen, separating it into its physical components within the gallery space. How do film theorists read these reformulations of the cinematic medium and their critique of what it is and has been? Theorizing Cinema through Contemporary Art: Expanding Cinema considers artworks that incorporate, restage, and re-present cinema's configurations of space, experience, presence/absence, production and consumption, technology, myth, perception, event, and temporality, thereby addressing the creation, appraisal, and evolution of film theory as channeled through contemporary art. Taking film theory as a blueprint for the moving image, and juxtaposing it with artworks that render cinema as a material object, this book unfolds a complex relationship between a theory and a practice that have often been seen as virtually incompatible, heightening our understanding of each and, more pertinently, their interactions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aArt and motion pictures. 0aMotion picturesxPhilosophy. 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aFilm Theory. 4aFilm, Media and Communication. 4aPhilosophy. 7aART / Film & Video.2bisacsh  aFilm Theory, Installation Art, Objectness.1 aBaschiera, Stefano, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButler, Alison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConnolly, Maeve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooper, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGibson, Sandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurphy, Jill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurphy, Jill, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNardelli, Matilde, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNorth, Kirstie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPantenburg, Volker, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPethő, Ágnes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRa